w monetary and political history unfolds in the tension between "moral economies of money" and "monetary silencing." Offering an introduction to money creation practices since the colonial era, the book enables readers to understand why most people are disconnected from knowledge about money creation today. At the same time, the book also allows readers to situate the recent prominence of Modern Monetary Theory (MMT) against a broader historical background. Historians of capitalism, economic and political sociologists, social theorists, anthropologists of money, and anyone seeking to understand monetary activism, will find this book helps to clarify present-day possibilities in light of historical processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCurrency questionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMonetary policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMoneyxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMoneyxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aUS history.  acredit.  adebt.  amonetary history.  amonetary theory.  amoral economy.  apublic finance.  asocial movements.  asociology of money.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107664860 cprintz978150362917240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363345240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633452423Coveruhttps://